\title{My Current Workflow (constantly changing)}

\p{
I have been using [todoist](todoist.com) and [habitify](habitify.me). I decided on these tools primarily because of their API availability. I wanted to be able to add / complete / see outstanding tasks or habits for the day without the allure of everything else my browser has to offer. Also visualization for my [[007S]].
}
\ul{
  \li{I had Claude write a little script to have my next tasks listed when clicked in my status bar, so I do not have to open the browser to check what I need to do today.}
}
\p{
It seems how to properly use these (todoist in particular) is the subject of much debate. Here, I will outline what I converged to / works for ME right now. I have broken down my system into a hierarchy:
\ol{
  \li{Higher level: how to actually choose what to do.}
  \li{Lower level: how to actually do the chosen task.}
}
}
\section{Figuring out what to do}{
  \p{
    This is effectively a task management system.
  }
    \strong{Work streams:} I took this name from my investment banker friends (sounds cool / important). Basically, these are groupings I have made and allocated time for each day. They roughly consist of the following:
    \ul{
      \li{Research / work (4hrs first thing in the morning):}
      \ul{
        \li{Active work towards new artifact or paper i.e. coding up ideas.}
        \li{In the absence of ideas, studying existing relevant papers.}
      }
      \li{Deliberate practice (2hrs after run / lunch):}
      \ul{
        \li{Name taken from [[calnewport]].}
        \li{As of writing this, a current example is spending ~2hrs a day writing / optimizing known kernels in CuTe / Pallas / NKI.}
        \li{Basically, something I need to understand or master for research that is not novel.}
      }
      \li{Extraneous Study (30min - 1hr):}
      \ul{
        \li{Things not directly related to research, but I am curious about.}
        \li{I try to maintain study of related computer science fields. Primarily, studying a textbook in something like [OS](0084), [computer architecture](P3GB), etc.}
      }
      \li{Habits / daily upkeep (1hr normally end of day):}
      \ul{
        \li{Mainly consists of reviewing Anki cards daily that come from extraneous study / deliberate practice.}
      }
    }
  }

\p{
To decide on the next task, I use a priority-based system:
\ol{
  \li{Things I will be working on today / until they are done. At most \strong{ONE} thing per work stream.}
  \li{The \em{backlog} of things to do next}
  \ul{
    \li{An index to find things to move to priority 1 for the next day} 
    \li{Keep relatively small to avoid the crippling nature of choice - roughly on the order of things I want done this week.}  
  }
  \li{A larger backlog of things - should be completed in the next month or so.}
  \li{Things I am not working on right now, or have any need to be completed any time soon.}
}
This idea is mainly based on the [MLFQ](4WG5), which has been proven effective for balancing response / turnaround time. To maintain this system, I have reviews each day and week (tracking with [habitify](habitify.me)) to make sure I stay consistent.
\ul{
  \li{\em{Daily review}:}
  \ul{
    \li{For each work stream,}
    \ul{
     \li{If I finished the allocated task for the day, get new task from priority 2.}
     \li{Else, do nothing and continue with the current task.}
    }
    \li{Review inbox and move new tasks to corresponding work stream for review on Friday.}
    \ul{
      \li{If immediately important, can move directly to priority 1 / 2.}
    }
    \li{Look at calendar for next day and timeblock work streams for the next day.}
    \ul{
      \li{Since PhD work is so hard to predict, I have found timeblocking any further than one day in advance to be a futile effort.}
    }
  }
  \li{\em{Weekly review}: }
  \ul{
    \li{Typically done on Fridays, so that I can dynamically allocate time on weekends if needed.}
    \li{For each work stream,}
    \ol{
     \li{Look in remaining priority 2 and priority 3 tasks.}
     \li{Define what I think a successful week would look like (e.g. if I get all these things done next week I will be happy).}
     \ul{
       \li{Look at calendar for week to guide this decision.}
     }
     \li{Get rid of at least two of those tasks (initial plan always too ambitious).}
     \li{Move / keep remaining tasks in priority 2.}
    }
    \li{Write [[007S]] for the week.}
  }
}
}
\section{What to do when actually working on a task}{
  \p{
This is the harder part (and requires the most discipline). When working on a task, especially a more open-ended one like research, it is very common that a million other things come up that seem immediately important. All of the sudden, you have a great idea for the research project you haven't worked on in months. 
  }
  \p{
  It is \strong{crucial} to collect and forget about these things until they are scheduled. This is the one thing I did take from [\em{Getting Things Done}](https://gettingthingsdone.com/). The system should \em{flow like water}. Making this achievable is where the todoist API becomes crucial.
  \ul{
    \li{I have a script bound by dwm that pops up vim for me to write down the task and, on save, it sends it to my inbox in todoist.}
    \li{I have more involved ones that allow me to actually allocate it to the specific work stream / priority if it is immediately obvious.}
  }
  Another thing that I have found useful to actually achieving this watery flow is the [pomodoro technique](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pomodoro_Technique). This basically lets me gaslight myself into thinking I can go to the other things as soon as the timer ends (which is intentionally always just close enough). By the end, I often no longer have this urge and can continue on the scheduled tasks.
  }
}
